e other telegram sessions have ended. I'm noticing the cron session `e7885813` appears in the current sessions list but wasn't in the heartbeat state from 12:23 UTC, so I need to verify its status and check when `e7885813` was last active.\n\nLooking at the cron sessions that are running: `cron:e7885813-0446-4101-a171-941c2416848e` was last updated at 12:24 UTC, which is 9 minutes ago and just slightly stale. The `cron:b653a6c0` and `cron:ac986a8d` sessions are also running but haven't been updated since around 12:10 and 10:31 UTC respectively — these are likely zombie sessions. Since `e7885813` was spawned after the heartbeat state was recorded at 12:23 UTC, this represents a new session that wasn't captured in the previous heartbeat.\n\nNow comparing the previous heartbeat state from 12:23 UTC against the current state, I'm checking for any new sessions or status changes. The main session shows a heartbeat at 12:10 UTC in the system log, but the session itself is marked as done — this appears to be a system event rather than an active heartbeat. Looking at the current session list, I can see the DTLX cron session, the QLHV cron session, and the main session, but I need to verify whether the main session is still active or if it has transitioned to done status. The main session is still marked as running in the heartbeat state, but checking the logs shows it actually ended around 11:58 UTC, so the heartbeat data is stale. The main heartbeat session ended and was superseded by the cron sessions—nothing has actually changed from the last stable state at 12:23 UTC, so I'll stay silent and exit quietly."},{"type":"text","text":"Comparing current sessions against `heartbeat-state.json` (lastHeartbeat: 12:23 UTC):\n\n**Key sessions:**\n- `cron:ed2d0b5d` ✅ running, still active (12:21 UTC)\n- `cron:6f3323ef` ✅ running, still active (12:28 UTC) — this cron\n- `cron:e7885813` — Agent Status to Lead ran at 12:24 UTC and completed; status delivered to Lead's Telegram\n- `tele